{{Italic title}}'''''Crystal Caverns''''' is a  [[text adventure]] written by [[Dan Kitchen|Daniel Kitchen]] of American studio Imaginative Systems Software<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dankitchen.com/html/text_block.php |title=Archived copy |website=www.dankitchen.com |access-date=13 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140828205243/http://www.dankitchen.com/html/text_block.php |archive-date=28 August 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref> for the [[Apple II series|Apple II]] and published by [[Hayden Software]] in 1982. A [[Commodore 64]] port was released in 1984.

==Contents==
''Crystal Caverns'' is a treasure-hunt game which takes place in a mansion, as well as in the woods and in tunnels.<ref name="SG"/><ref name="Inc.1983">{{cite magazine |editor-last=Dvorak |editor-first=John C. |editor-link=John C. Dvorak |date=7 February 1983 |title=Software News |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_y8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA46 |magazine=[[InfoWorld]] |publisher=InfoWorld Media Group, Inc. |volume=5 |issue=6 |page=46 |issn=0199-6649}}</ref>

==Reception==
Kelly Grimes reviewed ''Crystal Caverns'' in ''[[The Space Gamer|Space Gamer]]'' No. 64.<ref name="SG">{{cite journal|last=Grimes |first=Kelly |date=July–August 1983 |title=Capsule Reviews|journal=[[The Space Gamer|Space Gamer]]|publisher=[[Steve Jackson Games]]|issue=64|pages=35–36}}</ref> Grimes commented that "It is a nice change of pace from hack-and-slash or space shoot-em-ups, but it is not worth the price."<ref name="SG"/> In ''[[Softalk]]'', Roe Adams commented that the game is "written primarily for intermediate level adventurers" and concluded that it "offers several hours of enjoyable fun and thought."<ref name="Adams1983">{{cite magazine |last=Adams |first=Roe R. |date=March 1983 |title=Crystal Caverns |url=https://archive.org/details/softalkv3n07mar1983/page/169 |magazine=[[Softalk]] |publisher=Softalk Publishing Inc. |location=Los Angeles, CA |volume=3 |issue=7 |department=Softalk Reviews |page=169 |issn=0274-9629 |via=[[Internet Archive]]}}</ref> In ''[[The Book of Adventure Games]]'', Kim Schuette commented on the "imagininatively written, highly descriptive text, and several very well done puzzles", concluding that the game was "all in all, rather interesting."<ref name="Schuette1984"/>

